{"cursor":"11036","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox building\n| name = Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant sarcophagus native_name = image =\n| Chernobylreactor 1.jpg caption = The sarcophagus in 2006 alternate_name =\n| Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant Object Shelter map_type = Ukraine map_caption =\n| Location map building_type = Confinement shelter cost =\n| location = Covering Reactor 4 of the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant, within the\n| Chernobyl Exclusion Zone, near Prypiat location_town = location_country =\n| Ukraine coordinates_display = inline,title latitude = 51.389636 longitude =\n| 30.099033 start_date = June 1986 completion_date = November 1986 height =\n| references =\n}}\n\nThe 'Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant sarcophagus' or 'Object Shelter' is a massive\nconcrete envelope surrounding the nuclear reactor unit 4 of the Chernobyl\nNuclear Power Plant. It is designed to halt the release of radiation into the\natmosphere following the Chernobyl disaster on April 26, 1986 and encase the\nmost dangerous area. It is situated\nwithin a large, restricted area known as the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone. The\nofficial Russian name is No 4. ukrytiye, which means housing or covering, as\nopposed to sarcophagus. The sarcophagus locked in 200\ntons of radioactive corium, 30 tons of highly contaminated dust and 16 tons of\nuranium and plutonium. In 1996 it was deemed impossible to\nrepair the inside of the sarcophagus as radiation levels were estimated to be as\nhigh as 10,000 rÃ¶ntgens per hour (normal background radiation in cities is\nusually around 20-50 microrÃ¶ntgens per hour, and a lethal dose is 500 rÃ¶ntgens\nover 5 hours). A decision to replace\nthe sarcophagus with the New Safe Containment was taken, and a project to\nreconstruct the enclosure is underway.\n","linknr":257,"url":"Chernobyl_Nuclear_Power_Plant_sarcophagus","recorded":1375065998,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Chernobyl_Nuclear_Power_Plant_sarcophagus&action=edit","/w/index.php?titl